.SH NAME
nog \- tier-aware package manager for KognogOS
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nog
.I <command>
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ packages ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nog
is the package manager for KognogOS. It wraps
.BR pacman (8)
with a three-tier update management system, giving every package on the
system a protection level based on how critical it is.
.PP
Tier 1 packages — the kernel, bootloader, and core libraries — are never
updated automatically and require explicit sign-off. Tier 2 packages are
held for 10 days after a new version is published. Tier 3 packages update
freely on the next
.BR "nog update" .
.PP
.B nog
should always be run as your regular user. It escalates to root only where
genuinely required — by invoking
.B sudo pacman
for package transactions and
.B sudo tee
for writing
.IR /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml .
See the
.B PRIVILEGES AND SUDO
section below for the complete privilege model.
.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B nog install \fIpackage\fR [\fIpackage\fR...]
Install one or more packages. Tier 1 packages are blocked — use
.B nog unlock
first. Tier 2 packages proceed with a hold notice. Tier 3 packages install immediately.
.TP
.B nog remove \fIpackage\fR [\fIpackage\fR...]
Remove one or more packages via
.BR pacman (8).
.TP
.B nog update
Synchronize package databases and upgrade all packages. Tier 1 packages
are automatically excluded via
.BR pacman 's
.B --ignore
flag — they will not be touched under any circumstances.
.TP
.B nog search \fIquery\fR
Search for packages matching
.IR query .
Results are annotated with tier information:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B [Tier 1 — manual sign-off]
shown in red
.IP \(bu 2
.B [Tier 2 — 10d hold]
shown in yellow
.IP \(bu 2
.B [Tier 3 — fast-track]
shown in green
.RE
.TP
.B nog pin \fIpackage\fR \fB--tier=\fR\fI<1|2|3>\fR
Pin a package to a specific tier. The change is written immediately to
.IR /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
and survives reboots.
.TP
.B nog unlock \fIpackage\fR [\fB--promote\fR]
Unlock a Tier 1 package for manual upgrade. Without
.BR --promote ,
prints a confirmation message only. With
.BR --promote ,
calls
.BR pacman (8)
to install or upgrade the package immediately.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print help information.
.TP
.B \-V, \-\-version
Print version information.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/nog/nog.conf
Main nog configuration file. Defines paths, hold windows, and repo locations.
.TP
.I /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
Tier assignments for all managed packages. Edited directly by
.B nog pin
or manually by the system administrator.
.TP
.I /usr/bin/nog
The nog binary.
.
.SH TIER SYSTEM
.SS Tier 1 — Manual Sign-Off Required
Packages that are never auto-updated. Includes:
.BR linux ", " linux-zen ", " linux-lts ", " systemd ", " glibc ", "
.BR grub ", " efibootmgr ", " mkinitcpio ", " pacman ", " mesa .
.SS Tier 2 — 10-Day Hold
Key desktop applications held for 10 days after release. Includes:
.BR plasma-desktop ", " sddm ", " pipewire ", " networkmanager ", "
.BR firefox ", " dolphin ", " konsole ", " kate ", " grubforge .
.SS Tier 3 — Fast Track
Everything else. A minimal 3-day hold applies, then updates flow through
automatically on the next
.BR "nog update" .
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Install a package (nog prompts for sudo itself if needed):
.B nog install htop
.TP
Update the system:
.B nog update
.TP
Search with tier annotations:
.B nog search firefox
.TP
Pin a package to Tier 2:
.B nog pin htop --tier=2
.TP
Force-upgrade a held Tier 1 package:
.B nog unlock linux-zen --promote
.
.SH PRIVILEGES AND SUDO
.B nog
itself always runs as the invoking user; it is not designed to be run with
.BR sudo .
If you prefix
.B sudo nog
while an AUR helper is configured, nog detects the invocation (via
.B $SUDO_USER
or
.BR $SUDO_UID )
and exits with an error, because
.BR yay (8)
and
.BR paru (8)
refuse to run as root.
.PP
nog escalates to root in exactly two places, both as transparent
.BR sudo (8)
subprocess invocations:
.TP
.B sudo pacman -S | -R | -Syu ...
For package transactions during
.BR install ,
.BR remove ,
.BR update ,
and
.B "unlock --promote"
\(em but only when no AUR helper is configured. When a helper is configured,
nog hands the transaction to the helper (as the invoking user), and the
helper runs its own
.B sudo pacman
internally for the pacman step.
.TP
.B sudo tee /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
For the single file
.B nog
ever writes. Used only during
.BR "nog pin" .
The new file contents are rebuilt in memory and piped through
.BR tee ;
nog itself never runs with root privileges.
.PP
.B nog
never modifies any other file on your system \(em not
.IR /etc/pacman.conf ,
not
.IR /etc/pacman.d/ ,
not
.IR /var/lib/pacman/local/ ,
not the pacman keyring, and not
.IR /etc/sudoers .
It is a thin wrapper over
.BR pacman (8),
.BR yay (8),
or
.BR paru (8);
every install, remove, and upgrade is subject to pacman's signature
verification and conflict resolution, which nog cannot bypass.
.
